# Git safety — do not wipe working tree

## Hard rule

**Do not** run commands that overwrite or discard the user’s uncommitted changes **unless the user explicitly asks** for that exact operation (e.g. “run `git restore` on X”, “reset to HEAD”, “discard my local changes”).

This includes (non-exhaustive):

- `git restore` / `git checkout -- <paths>` (restoring files from index/HEAD)
- `git reset --hard`, `git clean -fd`
- `git checkout <branch>` when it would overwrite tracked files the user cares about without confirmation
- Any variant that **replaces working-tree files** with committed versions and **destroys hours of uncommitted edits**

## What to do instead

- Prefer **editing files** with apply_patch / search_replace to undo specific changes.
- If the user wants to “go back” conceptually, **ask** whether they mean editor undo (Ctrl+Z), **Timeline / Local History**, or a **targeted** revert of named files/commits — **never** assume they want `git restore` of the whole tree.
- If a git operation is needed, **state the risk** (“this will discard uncommitted changes in these files”) and wait for **explicit** confirmation tied to that risk.

## Rationale

`git restore` and similar commands are **not** the same as Ctrl+Z; they can permanently remove uncommitted work. The agent must not run them on its own initiative.
